04590nam a22008055i 9780231511209DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2006    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315112097 a10.7312/osto139002doi  a(DE-B1597)459191  a(OCoLC)1013954043  a(OCoLC)979831920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBF175.4.R44bO88 2007 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a201/.61501952221 aOstow, Mortimer, eauthor.10aSpirit, Mind, and Brain :bA Psychoanalytic Examination of Spirituality and Religion /cMortimer Ostow. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource :b0 halftones, 0 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Series in Science and Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Spirit -- tChapter 3. Mind -- tChapter 4. Religion -- tChapter 5. Brain -- tChapter 6. Mood Regulation -- tChapter 7. Apocalypse -- tChapter 8. Demonic Spirituality -- tChapter 9. Analyzing an Account of a Spiritual Experience -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPreeminent psychoanalyst Mortimer Ostow believes that early childhood emotional attachments form the cognitive underpinnings of spiritual experience and religious motivation. His hypothesis, which is verifiable, relies on psychological and neurobiological evidence but is respectful of the human need for spiritual value. Ostow begins by classifying the three parts of the spiritual experience: awe, Spirituality proper, and mysticism. After he pinpoints the psychological origins of these feelings in infancy, he discusses the foundations of religious sentiment and practice and the brain processes associated with spiritual experience. He then focuses on spirituality's relationship to mood regulation, and the role of negative spirituality in fostering religious fundamentalism and demonic possession.Ostow concludes with an analysis of an essay by the psychoanalyst Donald M. Marcus, who recounts his own spiritual experience during a Native American-style "vision quest" in the woods. Marcus's account demonstrates the constructive potential of spirituality and the way in which spirituality retrieves and recapitulates feelings of attachment to the mother.Persuasively and brilliantly argued, Spirit, Mind, and Brain brings the disciplines of religion, behavorial neuroscience, and philosophy to bear on a groundbreaking new method for understanding religious ritual and belief.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aPsychoanalysis and religion. 0aPsychology and religion. 0aPsychology, Religious. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/osto13900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231511209.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG